<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 93 / International Company News: Swissair loss deepens to SFr125m
at halfway
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZURICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SWISSAIR, the Swiss national airline, said its first-half loss widened to
SFr125m (Dollars 82.7m), compared with a loss of SFr116m in the same period
last year.
Profit before depreciation tumbled to SFr60m from SFr81m, and the company
said it would be difficult to meet its forecast of achieving a profit this
year.
Traffic volume improved 9.5 per cent and the overall load factor rose from
59.3 per cent to 62.5 per cent. However, revenues advanced only 2 per cent
to SFr2.47bn.
Swissair said the figures reflected 'the troubled state of the world's air
transport industry, which remains plagued by a ruinous price war'. The
company foresaw no improvement in revenues in the second half, and was
continuing to concentrate on cutting costs. Costs rose 3 per cent in the
first half, to SFr2.4bn, mainly because of fuel price increases.
Depreciation charges were down from SFr197m to SFr185m. Swissair depreciates
its aircraft rapidly and sells them while still relatively new. In recent
years, only the proceeds from aircraft sales, which are booked at the
year-end, have kept the group in profit.
The airline said it had already recorded 'sizeable book profits' on aircraft
sales this year.
</TEXT>
