<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 93 / Serbs to quit Sarajevo peaks: Promise seen as attempt to
forestall Nato air strikes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER, GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BOSNIAN SERBS agreed last night to a phased withdrawal from two strategic
mountains overlooking the besieged capital, Sarajevo, so as to allow United
Nations peacekeeping troops to occupy the peaks.
The agreement with UN commanders came after Bosnia's Moslem President Alija
Izetbegovic warned that peace talks in Geneva would collapse unless Nato
launched air strikes against Serb artillery around Sarajevo.
British Brigadier Vere Hayes said UN troops would occupy one of the peaks,
Mount Bjelasnica, this morning, when the Bosnian Serbs would pull out. He
said 150 French troops would go today to Mount Igman, nearer Sarajevo. The
Serbs have promised to quit this peak in the next few days.
The Serbs took the two mountains from Moslem forces in an unexpected
offensive last week, tightening their stranglehold on the Bosnian capital,
which has been under siege from Serb snipers and artillery for 16 months.
The pledges of withdrawal are an apparent attempt to forestall air strikes,
under discussion by the Nato alliance, and to put moral pressure on the
Moslem-led government to resume the Geneva talks on carving up Bosnia
largely on ethnic lines.
President Izetbegovic said earlier he thought air strikes against Serb
positions had 'never been closer' than now. 'I can say if there are no air
strikes, then there is no peace process, no negotiations,' he said in an
interview on the eve of scheduled talks with Bosnian Serb leader Mr Radovan
Karadzic and his Croat counterpart Mr Mate Boban.
However, Nato officials indicated Mr Izetbegovic's urging was likely to get
a cool reception when Nato ambassadors meet in Brussels today to discuss
possible air strikes. Nato did not intend the Bosnian Moslems to use the
hope of military intervention as an excuse for stalling talks, an official
said.
Today's meeting is expected to agree on logistics for any future air
strikes, out of a list of options finalised by the Nato military committee
in Brussels at the weekend. But officials warned that the allies were
unlikely today to authorise air strikes as there were still significant
differences about the scope and timing of any action.
In sharp criticism of western policy, Mr Izetbegovic singled out the UK for
undermining his government over the past 16 months of war. 'They had two
ways to help; either directly through intervention or to lift the arms
embargo,' he said. 'They did not do anything. Now we are left with our hands
tied.'
But indicating he had accepted Bosnia's tripartite division, he outlined
what he called his minimum requirements for Moslems: 'A fair map for the
Bosnian republic with access to the River Sava and the sea. We must have
territory covering an area suitable for 2.5m citizens. We need a geographic
and viable state.'
Editorial Comment, Page 11
</TEXT>
