<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In BBC Proms Live, broadcast simultaneously on BBC2 and in stereo on Radio
3, Claudio Abbado conducts the Gustav Mahler Youth Orchestra which he helped
to create, with players from all over the world (7.30). The first half
features Russian baritone Dmitri Hvorostovsky, winner of the BBC's Cardiff
Singer of the Year competition in 1989, in Mussorgsky's 'Songs And Dances Of
Death'. The second part, starting at about 8.15, is devoted to Bruckner's
vast Fifth Symphony, lasting almost one and a half hours. What does 'ghoti'
spell? Fish: 'gh' as in enough, 'o' as in women, and 'ti' as in nation. How
can you expect any child to learn to read in a language with such
illogicalities? World In Action takes up the fraught question of what
methods should be used to teach British children to read, given that the
'progressive' approach seems, if anything, rather less effective than the
old 'a for apple, b for bed' system (8.30 ITV). In Frank Stubbs Promotes
(9.00 ITV) the spiv is trying to promote Bulgarian ice dance champions. In
Travellers' Tales Wilfred Thesiger talks about his interest in Arabian
nomads (9.00 C4).
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4832 Radio Broadcasting Stations.
    P4833 Television Broadcasting Stations.
    P4841 Cable and Other Pay Television Services.
</IN>
