<TEXT>
LABOUR'S leadership was warned yesterday that to regard the south of England
as a no-go area for the party could cost it a majority government at the
next election.
Mr Bryan Gould, who resigned from the shadow cabinet last year over Europe,
said the party should offer the south 'something different and distinctive'.
He added: 'We must not allow ourselves to be browbeaten into accepting that
the south is somehow a no-go area for Labour or that we can break the Tory
hegemony only by trailing along on the Liberal Democrats' coat-tails.'
