FT  09 AUG 93 / Private sector wins big share of councils' cleaning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRIVATE contractors have won more than a third of council contracts for
building cleaning, the Institute of Public Finance says today in a survey on
compulsory competitive tendering.
The institute, the research arm of the Chartered Institute of Public Finance
and Accountancy, found that 119 private companies had won contracts for
cleaning buildings - more than for any other council service.
They account for 35.8 per cent of all contracts awarded. However, the
private sector has been most successful in winning small contracts, and its
share of the total council market by value is lower, at 15 per cent.
But the institute says their market share should grow in the next three
years, as governors use their powers under local management of schools to
contract out cleaning on individual contracts. Most school cleaning is now
organised by local authorities in contracts which are too large for most
private contractors to win.
The private sector has steadily gained ground over the past four years.
But the Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of Employment) 1981
regulations, known as Tupe, which implement the EC Acquired Rights
Directive, could inhibit further private-sector gains. The institute says
the regulations, which in many cases oblige private contractors to employ
council workers on their original pay, terms and conditions, cause concern
because 'it is estimated that up to 90 per cent of contract-cleaning costs
are taken up by labour requirements'.
The report adds: 'With competition within the industry so intense, success
in the market is often synonymous with the lowest labour costs.'
Costs of entry into the market are low because of cheap cleaning equipment,
while there are few economies of scale, allowing small companies to bid
successfully. The institute also suggests that experience with contract
cleaning in the National Health Service has helped the smaller players.
Regional variations are marked, with the private sector accounting for 53
per cent of contracts in the south-east and 49 per cent in London, but only
6 per cent in Wales and 12 per cent in the northernmost counties of England.
Conservative councils are far more likely to award work to the private
sector than Labour authorities, where 91 per cent of cleaning contracts stay
in-house.
CCT and the Private Sector, Volume 2. IPF, PO Box 4, Croydon, CR9 1AT.
Pounds 100 (Pounds 50 to local authorities).
</TEXT>
<XX>
