<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 93 / 'Rubber stamp' advisers win power to make their mark: How a
shadowy organisation will play a central role in the drive for more open
government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FIGHTING yesterday's battles can be as demanding as tackling today's
difficulties, as Mr William Waldegrave, the public-service minister, has
found in his efforts to bring greater openness to government.
His insistence that 'release' rather than 'retain' should be the watchword
in dealing with government files more than 30 years old has been as alien to
the culture of secrecy in Whitehall as the greater availability of current
information held by departments.
In theory, at least, Mr Waldegrave appears to have won some victories over
the mandarins' belief that there should be no need to know.
The white paper on open government, published last month, sets out changes
to the criteria for keeping files secret which are intended to ensure that
more documents should be made available. It also sets out the basic
principle that all records should be released after 30 years unless actual
damage would be caused by their publication.
But perhaps the greatest changes are to the role of the Advisory Council on
Public Records, called a 'rubber stamp' even by some of its members.
The 16-strong council is made up largely of politicians and academics and
chaired by Sir Thomas Bingham, the Master of the Rolls. Its task is to
advise the Lord Chancellor about which files should remain closed for more
than 30 years. Its powers are to be extended.
First, its remit will be expanded so that officials seeking to keep files
closed within departments must seek the approval of the council. Previously
a department could bypass the council by deciding to retain a file rather
than transfer it to the Public Records Office.
There are strict rules about what categories of documents can be retained by
departments, but some council members are not convinced that they are always
kept. One noted how, when some files from the 1940s finally found their way
on to the agenda, the department said merely that they had been
'overlooked'.
The detail of the second change has yet to be finalised, but goes to the
heart of members' complaints about how they carry out their work: it will
give them access to the documents.
Mr David Sumberg, the Tory MP for Bury South who sits on the council, is
clear that it would have been untenable to continue with previous practice.
Council members were presented at their quarterly meetings with long lists
of files which, they were told, were to remain closed, and were given only
the most general explanations for their closure.
'At the end of the day, either people can be trusted to see documents and
take decisions, or they can't,' he said.
Mr Waldegrave has made clear that some way of giving the council access to
the files will be found in future, but the recent letter to council members
from the official who organises did not say how this would be done.
The most likely outcome appears to be that the council will be able to look
at files as a last resort, and that knowing this power exists will deter
officials tempted to interpret the rules in a restrictive way.
If these changes work as Mr Waldegrave intends, they will represent a
serious assault on departments' ability to keep aged information out of the
public domain.
Mr Waldegrave's officials are clear that the assault could not have been
mounted without the 'broad philosophical support' of Mr John Major, the
prime minister, and the active backing of Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign
secretary.
They say that the 'open-mindedness' of Mr Hurd was crucial in putting
pressure on the Ministry of Defence, which had been seen as the department
least enthusiastic about unwrapping its past files.
And will Whitehall be defeated in any rearguard action it may try to mount
against the opening up of its past? Mr Terry Davis, MP for Birmingham Hodge
Hill and Labour's representative on the council, said: 'Ask me again in a
year's time.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
