<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 93 / Jordan warns of skills shortages
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ENGINEERING companies face imminent skill shortages, says Mr Bill Jordan,
president of the AEEU engineering and electrical union and chairman of the
training committee of the Confederation of Shipbuilding and Engineering
Unions.
Mr Jordan is to meet Mr David Hunt, the employment secretary, to discuss his
concern about the shortage of craft, technical and supervisory skills that
will result when demand picks up, and to present a CSEU-led policy
initiative on training.
The initiative argues for more multi-skilling in engineering and wants to
increase trade union involvement in training programmes. It recommends the
establishment of joint committees to monitor progress and liaise with
training and enterprise councils.
The initiative prepared by the CSEU includes trade union involvement in the
redesign of National Vocational Qualifications in manufacturing and
engineering - some of which it claims have been diluted in their breadth of
skills because of costs. Others, it says, are too narrow and task-specific.
The confederation, while setting out the respective responsibilities of the
government, employers and trainees, ideally would like some form of national
levy to cover the cost of the training.
Engineering the Future: The Case for New Skills in a Modern Industry. CSEU,
140 Walworth Road, London SE17 IJW.
