<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 93 / Scargill takes aim at area's Pounds 5.8m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A PLAN by Mr Arthur Scargill, president of the National Union of
Mineworkers, to take over the Pounds 5.8m assets of the union's Yorkshire
area to ease the NUM's financial crisis has come under sharp attack from a
leading Yorkshire official.
Mr John Walsh, the area's agent and assistant general secretary, warns in an
internal document that the scheme threatens to plunge the Yorkshire area,
which is the union's largest and richest, into deficit and compel large
increases in members' contributions. He has been forbidden by other
Yorkshire officials to circulate his document.
Mr Scargill wants to centralise the NUM by taking over control of the
union's areas, which have considerable financial and administrative
autonomy. Other NUM areas are also resisting his centralising moves.
Yorkshire - like other NUM areas - is registered as a separate body with its
own accounts and assets, reflecting the NUM's federal character. Mr Scargill
was president of the Yorkshire area before he was elected to the national
presidency 12 years ago.
Yet the Yorkshire area council agreed last month to proceed with a transfer
of engagements in a move to integrate the area fully into the national
union. But such a step could be made legally only with members' approval in
a ballot. This is expected to take place before the end of the year.
Mr Scargill's plan is to create a new trust fund that would administer
Yorkshire's total spending.
A sharp decline in membership - down from 245,000 in 1982 to about 30,000
today - and the cost of the 1984-85 strike has put considerable strain on
NUM finances.
Last year the union had a small surplus of Pounds 31,686 according to
figures just submitted to the Certification Office by Mr Scargill, but
suffered a Pounds 69,772 negative cashflow on its operating expenses.
Just 32,947 members contributed Pounds 1.4m to the union fund's nationally
last year, while investment income totalled Pounds 233,615. But
headquarters' administrative costs alone accounted for Pounds 1.3m of the
union's total expenditure of Pounds 1.7m.
Priority for the proposed trust's funds would first be to honour existing
legal obligations and to pay benefits. But the other main uses of the fund
would be to cover national office expenses, additional salary costs and any
redundancy or severance money for full-time officers at national as well as
area level.
Mr Walsh estimates the fund's total income could amount to between Pounds
640,000 and Pounds 870,000 a year. He says the plan would mean raising
subscriptions and cutting benefits for Yorkshire members.
Mr Scargill has denied Mr Walsh's calculations.
</TEXT>
<XX>
