<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 93 / Deportation rules to be reviewed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Home Office confirmed yesterday that it intends to carry out a joint
review with the Metropolitan police of procedures used in cases of
deportation that require an arrest. This follows the death of Joy Gardner
last Sunday.
The review will look at the specific rules that cover the behaviour of
police and immigration officers before an illegal immigrant is arrested for
deportation.
The review is less than the full public inquiry requested by Mrs Gardner's
family. It will be carried out by senior immigration officers and a senior
officer from the Metropolitan police.
The inquiry will investigate in particular the equipment used by the
authorities to restrain violent deportees. Mrs Gardner died after being
subdued in a struggle with officers trying to arrest her for deportation at
her flat in Hornsey, north London.
The proposed joint review is in addition to the internal investigation
already being carried out by the Home Office into the work of Scotland
Yard's deportation unit.
Yesterday Mrs Teresa Gorman, Tory MP for Billericay, said that while she
regretted Mrs Gardner's death, she had been 'bumming on the social services
for five years'. Mrs Gorman told the BBC: 'She has cost the . . . taxpayer
an enormous amount of money. If she had gone quietly none of this would have
happened.'
</TEXT>
