<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 93 / Hosokawa cabinet balances rivalries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S newly installed prime minister, Mr Morihiro Hosokawa, early today
named a key coalition ally, Mr Tsutomu Hata, as foreign minister and deputy
premier.
In announcing his cabinet line-up, Mr Hosokawa completed a delicate
balancing act. He has put together a cabinet new enough to keep his
just-elected seven-party coalition happy, but experienced enough to ensure
continuity in government.
The core posts went to defectors from the Liberal Democratic party, now in
opposition after nearly 40 years in office. But Mr Hosokawa still found room
in the cabinet for a record three women and for two non-politicians.
Mr Hata's party, the Japan Renewal party, also picked up the posts of
agriculture minister, minister of international trade and industry, and
finance, which went to a former bureaucrat, Mr Hirohisa Fujii.
After his appointment was announced, Mr Hata said that a priority for him
would be to apologise clearly for wartime brutality in the hope of securing
a full reconciliation with other Asian countries. 'We have to find the right
words,' he said.
Other leaders of coalition parties were also rewarded with posts, including
Mr Sadao Yamahana, the Social Democratic party leader, who is the minister
responsible for political reform, which is the the policy priority of the
Hosokawa government.
Mr Hata was one of the key defectors who brought down the former Liberal
Democratic party government over its failure to enact political reforms.
The cabinet list came two days after Mr Hosokawa was elected prime minister
in a parliamentary vote that put the seal on the LDP's setback in the
general election on July 18.
There were intense negotiations to balance the interests of the seven
parties involved.
Mr Hosokawa appointed a woman, Ms Manae Kubota, to the post of Economic
Planning Agency director. The 68-year-old Ms Kubota belongs to the Social
Democratic party and has served in the Upper House of parliament.
The labour minister is Chikara Sakaguchi, a member of the Buddhist-backed
Komeito Party.
While Mr Hosokawa has been working out his cabinet, Japan's bureaucrats have
continued to do things their way.
Without consulting the new administration, finance ministry officials have
been telling other ministries that spending in next year's budget will
increase by only 3 per cent.
The ministries are supposed to present their spending plans to the finance
ministry by the end of this month, and appear to be ready to continue the
plans made under LDP rule.
Coalition horse rides into town, Page 11
</TEXT>
