<HEADLINE>
FT  07 AUG 93 / Gore gives Clinton victory in Senate on budget bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton last night scored a crucial political victory when
his compromise budget bill cleared its final congressional hurdle. After a
tense day of debate and behind-the-scenes arm-twisting, the Senate approved
the measure by the narrowest possible margin - the casting vote of
Vice-President Al Gore.
The victory was even narrower than the one achieved on Thursday night in the
House of Representatives, when the bill was passed by a majority of just two
votes.
Until the last minute the Senate vote was in doubt, with everything resting
on the decision of Senator Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, who, despite a 90-minute
meeting with Mr Clinton earlier in the day, had refused to make his position
known.
In his speech to the Senate, Mr Kerrey conceded he had taken 'too long' to
reach his decision. 'My head, I can say, aches with all the thinking, but my
heart aches with the conclusion - that I will vote yes for a bill which
challenges America too little,' he said.
The pressure on Mr Kerrey from fellow Democrats and promises from Mr Clinton
that further spending cuts would be considered later this year finally swung
him to cast his vote in favour of the legislation.
The passage of the bill, which aims to narrow the budget deficit by Dollars
496bn (Pounds 332.8bn) over the next five years, was seen by many leading
Democrats as critical to Mr Clinton's political authority and to his
campaign pledges to turn the American economy around.
The president had argued that the bill was needed to create the momentum for
further reform proposals, especially on health and welfare. It also
represented an at least temporary end to the 'gridlock' which had for the
past 12 years bedevilled relations between the president and Congress.
Mr Leon Panetta, the White House budget director, stressed yesterday that
winning the vote was the best chance for the Democrats to show that they
could govern the country even without a single Republican vote.
The result in the House the night before had been in doubt with Mr Clinton
making a vital telephone call to a wavering congresswoman only 15 minutes
before the vote.
Mrs Marjorie Margolies-Mezvinsky, who had said she would vote against the
bill, then switched sides and to Democrat applause gave Mr Clinton his
majority, 218-216. Had she kept to her original intention, the bill would
have been a vote short of the required 218.
Mr Clinton has campaigned intensively for the bill which will raise Dollars
241bn in revenue, largely by raising income tax for the wealthiest
Americans, and imposing Dollars 255bn in spending cuts, to fall heavily on
the military.
But he has faced opposition within the conservative wing of his own party,
which wants deeper spending cuts to achieve a more substantial deficit
reduction. On Thursday night in the House, 41 Democrats opposed the
compromise bill compared with 38 when the first version of the legislation
was passed.
</TEXT>
