<HEADLINE>
FT  07 AUG 93 / London Stock Exchange: Hickson tumbles
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, CHRISTOPHER PRICE and ZHANG TINGTING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Speciality chemicals group Hickson International fell sharply after the news
of an explosion at one of its plants, was joined by an analyst's sell
recommendation and confirmation that a leading institutional shareholder had
reduced its equity stake.
The shares were weakened initially by news of the explosion which had
destroyed one of Hickson's fine chemicals manufacturing plants at
Ringaskiddy, in the Irish Republic.
The explosion follows a fire last September at the company's plant in
Castleford Yorkshire which killed five staff. The fire led to a Pounds
250,000 fine and Pounds 150,000 costs a month ago.
After yesterday's news, Mr Martin Evans, chemicals analyst with Hoare
Govett, turned seller of the stock.
He said the explosion would hit investor confidence in the management and
would lead to uncertainty over future production.
He also said that a prospective p/e of 17 times was too high in the light of
the troubles and a sector rating of 15 times earning and argued that the
shares deserved to fall a further 10 per cent.
Finally, Hickson confirmed yesterday that Gartmore, one of its leading
shareholders, had sold 4.9m shares earlier in the week and taken its stake
down to 2.2 per cent.
Hickson's share price tumbled 14 to 194p with 1.1m shares changing hands.
The announcement by Thorn EMI that negotiations to sell its defence
electronics buisness to GEC had been called off hit both companies' shares.
Leisure analysts said that the fall in Thorn's price - down 10 at 935p -
reflected not only the market's immediate disappointment but also the fact
that no other suitor could be called to mind immediately. GEC shares slipped
a penny to 343 1/2 p.
The two companies admitted last month that they were in discussions, with a
price tag of Pounds 160m mentioned by industry specialists.
Standard Chartered gained 25 to 885p ahead of interim figures on Thursday as
buying pressure was accentuated by a bear squeeze.
Reed International slid a further 8 to 652p, apparently affected by the
caution of Dutch investors in Reed Elsevier over current trading conditions
and future prospects for the combined group.
Ms Chris Munro, media analyst at Hoare Govett, believes that the encouraging
interim figures, together with the group's exposure to advertising and
prospects of success in the Official Airline Guides deal will reassure both
Dutch and British investors.
Reuters Holdings again rose on enthusiastic US buying and strong UK
recommendations in a thin market. The shares closed 20 firmer at 1535p.
SG Warburg reiterated its buy recommendation for Carlton Communications on
an earnings growth forecast of 25 per cent. The shares appreciated 11 to
764p.
In the media agencies sector, Saatchi &amp; Saatchi went up 4 to 174 on a market
forecast that Tuesday will bring news of interim profits of around Pounds
9m.
A downgrade in United Biscuits undermined the shares which slid 8 to 381p.
Hoare Govett chopped its profit forecast by Pounds 7m to Pounds 198m,
blaming low food price inflation.
Board changes and fresh investment at Amber Day lifted the shares 7 to 71p.
An unfulfilled order was said to be holding Dixons up, the shares finishing
9 ahead at 236p. Sears, said to be benefiting from a Smith New Court
upgrade, was up 5 at 109p.
Glaxo failed to benefit from yesterday's rally after Nomura reiterated its
'sell' recommendation because of the potential downside of the forthcoming
Zantac patent case.
The shares closed unchanged at 529p.
</TEXT>
