<HEADLINE>
FT  07 AUG 93 / UK Company News: Hickson chemical plant damaged by explosion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HICKSON International, the speciality chemicals and timber treatment group,
was hit by its second disaster within 12 months yesterday when an explosion
badly damaged one of its fine chemicals manufacturing plants in the Irish
Republic.
The blast at the site in Ring-askiddy, County Cork, caused damaged estimated
initially at several million pounds.
The plant, one of two on the site, was used to make active and intermediate
ingredients for pharmaceutical companies throughout the world and is the
only one run by Hickson to have received approval from the US Food and Drug
Administration.
Mr Michael Rowley, group finance director, said: 'The plant has been badly
damaged and production will be disrupted for some months. However, we do
have inventories of the finished product and the damage and loss of business
is fully covered by insurance.
The explosion will be a further blow to investor confidence, which was
dented last autumn after a fire at another of the company's sites in
Castleford, West Yorkshire, killed five staff and landed Hickson with a
Pounds 250,000 fine and Pounds 150,000 costs.
Earlier this week one of the Gartmore stable of investment funds, which had
been a leading Hickson shareholder, placed 4.9m shares in the market and
reduced its stake to 2.2 per cent. Yesterday, Hickson's share price fell 14p
to 194p.
</TEXT>
