<HEADLINE>
FT  07 AUG 93 / UK Company News: Taking a gamble on the switch - The reverse
takeover of Crockfords by TV-am
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DIRECTORS of TV-am, the breakfast television company which lost its
licence, yesterday took a final gamble and bought Crockfords, the Mayfair
casino in a reverse takeover.
The deal will be paid for by a rights issue which will raise Pounds 50m and
give the company, to be known as Crockfords, a market capitalisation of
Pounds 90m.
Mr Richard Redmayne, a director of TV-am who will remain a non-executive
director of Crockfords, said yesterday: 'I think it is a very good deal
which offers TV-am shareholders a very real alternative.'
After losing its licence to Good Morning Television, TV-am was planning a
voluntary liquidation until it was approached by Mr Garry Nesbitt, chairman
of Crockfords.
He was not only keen to get a Stock Exchange listing for his casino group
but also wanted to 'acquire' some of TV-am's institutional shareholders, who
range from Phillips &amp; Drew and Scottish Amicable to Schroders and Fidelity.
Under the conditional deal, TV-am will acquire all the issued share capital
of Crockfords in return for 71.25m ordinary shares in TV-am credited as
fully paid. These shares are worth Pounds 64.1m at the offer price of 90p.
Of the shares, 26.8m will go to the vendors and 44.3m will be offered as
part of the rights issue. The issue is on the basis of 9-for-2. Of the
Pounds 50m to be raised from the issue, Pounds 39.9m will go to the vendors
and the rest, together with about Pounds 9m of TV-am cash, will be used to
pay off remaining Crockfords debt.
Hambros Bank, which is sponsoring the deal, is also offering to buy up to 20
per cent of the existing ordinary TV-am shares to provide a cash alternative
of 18p.
Not all TV-am directors were happy with the Crockfords deal. Mr Stratos
Zagraphos, who was its finance director, resigned last month because he felt
he did not know enough about the casino business to carry out proper due
diligence.
Pro forma earnings per share of the enlarged group were 12.6p for the year
to December 1992 and 7p for the 24 weeks ending June 13 1993. The pro forma
earnings multiple at the offer price is 7.1 times.
Operating profits at Crockfords have ranged from Pounds 7.4m in 1990 to
Pounds 19.8m last year. The figure for the first half of this year is Pounds
11.4m.
The company warns, however, that in each of the last three financial years
Crockfords top 10 players have accounted for 5 per cent of profits although
the members of the 'exceptional players' list changed over the period.
'A small group of players can have a dramatic impact on the performance of
an up-market casino in any given period,' the Hambros statement said.
Last year, if the current proposals had been implemented, there would have
been a dividend of 5.2p.
Dealings in the shares are due to start on September 1.
</TEXT>
