FT  07 AUG 93 / UK Company News: Thorn EMI and GEC end defence sale talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THORN EMI has failed in its bid to sell its defence electronics business to
GEC. The talks between the two companies, which had been progressing for
months, broke down earlier this week.
No reason was given for the breakdown, but analysts believe price was a
serious consideration. Figures of about Pounds 160m were rumoured at an
earlier stage.
Thorn EMI's shares, which have been weakening since the middle of the weak,
dropped a further 10p to 935p yesterday.
Thorn's strategy remains to concentrate on its core music and TV rental
businesses, and it is anxious to find another buyer. It is one of the
world's top three in publishing and recorded music, and Radio Rentals is the
world's biggest rental business.
Thorn has for some time been seeking a buyer for its defence business, which
includes radar and infra-red imaging. It employs about 4,300 people and has
a turnover of some Pounds 425m.
Since 1990 the company has disposed of numerous non-core businesses. The
most recent was light fittings, recently bought by a management buy-out team
for Pounds 162m. The controlling stake in Thames TV was also sold this year.
The sale would have strengthened GEC's dominant position in defence
electronics, and was thought a few weeks ago to be on the verge of
completion.
