<HEADLINE>
FT  07 AUG 93 / Lib Dems gain 19 seats by targeting
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Liberal Democrats have made a net gain of 19 seats in the 183 local
authority by-elections that have been held since the county council
elections at the beginning of May.
According to the Local Government Chronicle Elections Centre at the
University of Plymouth this is the result of successful targeting of
resources at promising seats by the Liberal Democrats, and could be
translated into future gains of parliamentary seats.
Mr Collin Rallings and Mr Michael Thrasher, from the university, pointed out
that the Liberal Democrats had gained four seats in the south-west in last
year's general election, even though their share of the national vote fell
by 4.5 per cent.
Writing in Local Government Chronicle, they concluded: 'Unless the Tories
manage to increase their vote at the next election, they are likely to lose
at least a handful of seats to the Liberal Democrats in southern England.'
Thirteen of the 19 gains were from the Conservatives, with four from Labour
and two from others.
