<HEADLINE>
FT  07 AUG 93 / Jury may order big asbestos penalties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A MISSISSIPPI jury has found two US companies, Westinghouse Electric and
Dresser Industries, and an Australian company, Colonial Sugar Refinery,
guilty of wrongfully distributing products containing asbestos, and ordered
them to pay damages and penalties that could total hundreds of millions of
dollars, Patrick Harverson writes from New York.
Another US company, Uniroyal, was also found guilty but will not be affected
by the verdict because it had already settled during the trial.
The jury in the four-month trial, which was a consolidation of 9,600
individual asbestos-exposure lawsuits, ruled in favour of plaintiffs who
claimed they suffered lung injuries from inhaling products containing
asbestos fibres. The four companies were held liable for intentionally and
maliciously distributing defective, asbestos-bearing products.
The jury will begin considering how much to award as punitive damages today.
The jury awarded damages of Dollars 9.26m (Pounds 6.2m) to just six
representative plaintiffs whose cases were part of the trial. Three other
representative plaintiffs were found not to be eligible for compensation.
Five smaller defendant companies named in the lawsuit were found not guilty.
</TEXT>
